The paper discusses the use of emerging non-volatile memories (eNVMs) for in-memory processing to improve performance and energy efficiency for data-intensive applications. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including cs.AR (Architecture), cs.DB (Databases), cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.SY (Systems and Control). However, given the focus on hardware architecture and memory technologies, cs.AR is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of in-memory processing for specific applications, such as machine learning and graph processing, which could also suggest cs.NE and cs.DB as likely sub-categories.
